New York The euro rose on Thursday alongside sterling and bond yields as a slew of hawkish comments from central banks signaled the era of ultra-loose monetary policy is ready to sunset across the Atlantic.The dollar index touched its lowest since October -before Donald Trump was elected US president as investors shifted to the view that the US Federal Reserve might not be the only game in town when it comes to higher interest rates.With the Fed green-lighting dividends and buybacks in major banks as part of another round of stress tests, financial stocks rose but not enough to offset declines in technology and interest-rate sensitive sectors."Part of the reason why tech is down today is the steam in the recent rotation out of some of big tech winners and into banks," said Michael Scanlon, portfolio manager at Manulife Asset Management in Boston.The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 141.81 points, or 0.66%, to 21,312.8, the S&amp;P 500 lost 19.3 points, or 0.79%, to 2,421.39 and the Nasdaq Composite dropped 92.96 points, or 1.49%, to 6,141.46.European shares failed to hold onto early gains. The pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index lost 1.36% and MSCI s gauge of stocks across the globe shed 0.52%. Emerging market stocks lost 0.08%. MSCI s broadest index of Asia-Pacific shares outside Japan closed 0.59% higher, while Japan s Nikkei rose 0.45%. As euro zone bond yields rallied, the euro surged to as high as $1.1434, its strongest since May 2016. The dollar index fell 0.31%, with the euro up 0.4% to $1.1421.Bank of England Governor Mark Carney surprised many on Wednesday by conceding a hike was likely to be needed as the economy came closer to running at full capacity.That sent sterling above $1.30 on Thursday for the first time in five weeks, leaving it close to its highest levels in nine months. The pound was last trading at $1.2986, up 0.48% on the day.The Bank of Canada had its say, with two top policymakers this week suggesting they might tighten monetary policy as early as July.The Canadian dollar strengthened 0.21% versus the greenback at 1.301.30 per dollar."The shifting monetary policy trajectories of other central banks is making other currencies more attractive relative to the US dollar," said Kathy Lien, managing director at BK Asset Management in New York.The Japanese yen was flat versus the greenback at 112.29 per dollar.Benchmark US Treasury yields rose to five-week highs in sympathy with higher European government debt yields, as investors evaluated the likelihood of less accommodative policy.Treasury 10-year notes last fell 12/32 in price to yield 2.2648%, from 2.223% late on Wednesday.Oil futures edged up less than 1% after hitting a two-week high, extending a rally into a sixth straight session after a decline in weekly US crude production temporarily alleviated concerns about deepening oversupply.US crude rose 0.51% to $44.97 per barrel and Brent was last at $47.42, up 0.23% on the day.Gold fell as central bank comments lifted bond yields.Spot gold dropped 0.4% to $1,243.55 an ounce.US gold futures fell 0.41% to $1,244.00 an ounce.Copper rose 0.93% to $5,935.50 a tonne.Reuters